Each woman with short hair and that type of nose is the preview of life crumbling into a reality that isn't compatible with you, the old one. There isn't ice melting on this side; the sun is so bright the only shape allowed is liquid. The space so wide songs now don't bounce back, neither does memory, both just float infinitely touching everybody else but me. I've moved far but I am still a bit us, a bit someone who doesn’t exist but is clearly here with you.

I started this book because I was not able to talk to other people about you

but maybe I just didn’t want to light some of your corners
I didn’t want to learn where I would fail, where would you
I didn’t want to watch the end arrive,
and realize it didn’t come from far but from within
never sure if it was predicted by my own words 
or brought by them

I just watched it all, so quietly

but I did; I did all of those things and I bled on your back when I had to forget who you were in Mexico; when your body blocked the beautiful view and I had to close my eyes not to imagine but to see. My hand touching others, lighting your face on fire, bending your stomach towards our past. Both burning, for so long, so slowly.

and I just stayed and watched it all, so quietly

The image of your neck stretching towards your back is sexy and sad and I can’t avoid feeling some sort of pleasure watching your frustration on the screen. You care. I have fallen in love somewhere along the way, and keep finding pieces of love and attraction scattered around, waiting for the right moment to be found and unified into something solid enough to be held. I am not used to that. Love has always worked the other way around; a mysterious rock falls on your reality and destroys the limit to what you thought someone could become. Eventually, it breaks; pieces equally scattered in both scenarios. I wonder what it means, to do this process backward. If it's right, wrong, or just selfish curiosity. I wonder where you are, what your pieces look like; if you’re holding something or if a rock has ever hit you.
Joyce Staton

May 20, 2022

Did rats stare as intensely into my eyes last year?

The smell of cheap bleach and pee and trash is starting to feel like home. The exact same dogs scream at Aita on our walk, a husky and a mud, and the school where she used to play ball is now a massive pile of dirt. Foster Sundry has new color block tables outside, but Gonzalo isn’t here ordering us lattes. 

I am walking, walking everywhere, to process not being in Los Angeles and to take in the lack of trees, the excess of people. Crossing paths with Hinge matches, looking over my shoulder to check if they do, too. Home has been built on choices, on familiar faces, on conquering a language word by word, talk by talk, stranger by stranger. 

I forgot how all my muscles tensed up the day I met you, the exact moment I decided through your face to move to this city; but I remember the dog peeing on the corner, the woman with the not long enough skirt, fearing becoming as old as them, alone in Los Angeles. In a year, with the distance and the sun blinding me again, I will watch both the city and yourself become the same thing: that exact feeling that I can't describe but that is hiding every place you haven't seen before.

It is the south, the darkness, all the places you seem to be from. It’s your hand holding his, an unknown warmth leaving his body and tainting every word until one day it leaves yours as well. It’s the water, our feet looking like this death we talk about for days in an hour. It’s the past embedded in every choice that made these sentences and the present possible. It’s everyone leaving and pretending it isn’t here; the morning, these trees, that kind of black turned blue turned light guiding us inside, towards every thing that hasn’t happened yet.

Rauelsson, Oregon, Peter and Laura

I was 21 when Raul took me on a trip after having met me for a coffee in Madrid. I listened to his song Hourglass I the entire flight there, excited and confused, navigating the new pleasure of doing something without knowing why. We crossed the Oregon forests towards the beach, and Peter waited for us outside in the cold. My english was terrible, so I couldn't tell him I knew who he was, I couldn't tell him I knew every word of his song Sideline, I couldn’t tell him that his album was the only one i would listen to from beginning to end, song by song, always in order. I just remained silent, taking in the space, how he moved with his violin, raul smiling quietly at the piano and the silky sound of the hammers hitting the fabric instead of what they were supposed to. It was the strangest feeling; to arrive to this place faster than my own reality, and, for years after that, to be always too early or too late. Never at the exact right time.

words words words
and something in you, making them funny

little muscles in my face exist only then,
when laughing hurts
when you love the only way you know how

words words words
and something in me silencing them

little muscles in your chest exist only then,
when it hurts,
when I love the only way I’ve always wanted to be loved 

words words words
and the little house we’ve built, in secret,
exists only then, when it doesn’t hurt,
when I press my face against your chest 
and our love looks the exact same way

once again 
you throw the rock and hide the hand
as if I don’t already know what isn’t seen, what isn’t said
as if I am not the surface layer of a lake, a puddle, a mirror hiding what’s within

come on
throw another pebble
let them sink into me
let them find the further ends
let me find out if we would drown with them
if the mirror would break into pieces or more waves

reveal your hands and hold my fears first
I’m just another tired child resting on your ankles
finding safety in white socks, in sharp bones 

when is time, draw a line around my body
I'll be ready, to leave the ground
or to keep playing dead
